## CODING STANDARDS (ALL AGENTS MUST FOLLOW)

### Dart / Flutter Conventions
- Use `dart format` with 80-char line length
- Prefer `const` constructors everywhere possible
- Use `final` for all variables that don't need reassignment
- Name files in `snake_case`, classes in `PascalCase`, variables/functions in `camelCase`
- Every public API must have a dartdoc comment
- No `print()` in production code - use a logger service
- Always handle errors with `Either<Failure, Success>` pattern or `AsyncValue` from Riverpod

### Architecture Rules
```
lib/
  core/                          # Shared foundation
    constants/                   # App-wide constants, API keys (from env)
    theme/                       # ThemeData, colors, text styles, gradients
    utils/                       # Helpers, extensions, formatters
    error/                       # Failure classes, error handling
    di/                          # Dependency injection setup (get_it)
    router/                      # go_router configuration
    widgets/                     # Base widget classes
  features/                      # Feature modules (1 folder per module)
    auth/
      data/
        models/                  # Firestore DTOs, JSON serialization
        datasources/             # Remote (Firebase) + Local (Hive/SQLite)
        repositories/            # Repository implementations
      domain/
        entities/                # Pure Dart objects (no Firebase deps)
        repositories/            # Abstract repository interfaces
        usecases/                # Business logic units
      presentation/
        screens/                 # Full page widgets
        widgets/                 # Feature-specific widgets
        providers/               # Riverpod providers
    activity/                    # Same structure as auth
    diet/
    workout/
    health/
    mental_wellbeing/
    community/
    profile/
    home/
    fitcoins/
  services/                      # Cross-cutting services
    ai_service.dart              # Gemini API wrapper
    notification_service.dart
    health_connect_service.dart  # Android Health Connect
    healthkit_service.dart       # iOS HealthKit
    analytics_service.dart       # Firebase Analytics
    location_service.dart        # GPS tracking
    sync_service.dart            # Offline sync manager
  shared/
    widgets/                     # Reusable UI components
      glass_card.dart
      neon_button.dart
      gradient_app_bar.dart
      chart_wrapper.dart
      shimmer_loading.dart
      module_summary_card.dart
    models/                      # Shared data models
    extensions/                  # Dart extensions
```

### State Management (Riverpod)
- Use `@riverpod` annotation (code generation) for all providers
- Prefer `AsyncNotifier` for stateful logic with async operations
- Use `ref.watch()` in build methods, `ref.read()` in callbacks
- Keep providers small and composable
- Every provider file ends with `_provider.dart`

### Firebase / Backend Rules
- ALL Firestore access goes through repository classes - never call Firestore directly from UI
- Repository interfaces live in `domain/repositories/` (abstract classes)
- Repository implementations live in `data/repositories/`
- This abstraction enables future migration to Supabase without touching UI or domain logic
- Use Firebase security rules - never trust the client
- Cloud Functions for server-side validation and AI processing
- Store sensitive keys in Firebase Remote Config, not in code

### Repository Pattern (Migration-Ready)
```dart
// domain/repositories/activity_repository.dart (INTERFACE)
abstract class ActivityRepository {
  Future<Either<Failure, List<Activity>>> getActivities(String userId);
  Future<Either<Failure, Activity>> saveActivity(Activity activity);
  Stream<List<Activity>> watchActivities(String userId);
}

// data/repositories/firebase_activity_repository.dart (IMPLEMENTATION)
class FirebaseActivityRepository implements ActivityRepository {
  final FirebaseFirestore _firestore;
  // ... Firebase-specific implementation
}

// FUTURE: data/repositories/supabase_activity_repository.dart
// class SupabaseActivityRepository implements ActivityRepository { ... }
```

### UI / Design Rules
- Dark theme is DEFAULT. Light theme is optional.
- All colors come from `core/theme/app_colors.dart` - never hardcode hex values
- Glassmorphism cards use: `BackdropFilter` + `ClipRRect` + semi-transparent background
- Neon glow effects: `BoxShadow` with neon color and blur radius 15-25
- Animations: use `Lottie` for complex, `AnimatedContainer`/`Hero` for simple transitions
- Bottom navigation with 5 tabs: Home, Activity, Diet, Workout, Profile
- Each module accessed via Home cards OR bottom nav sub-navigation
- All screens must be responsive (mobile portrait primary, landscape optional, web adaptive)
- Reference UI screenshots from `docs/ui_screenshots/` folder when available

### Testing Standards
- Every repository must have unit tests
- Every provider/notifier must have unit tests
- Critical UI flows (onboarding, activity tracking, meal logging) need widget tests
- Integration tests for auth flow and data sync
- Test files mirror source structure: `test/features/activity/...`
- Use `mocktail` for mocking

### Git Conventions
- Branch naming: `feature/activity-gps-tracking`, `fix/diet-calorie-calc`, `chore/update-deps`
- Commit messages: `feat(activity): add GPS route polyline rendering`
- PR = 1 feature or fix, never mix concerns
- Squash merge to main

